[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] A **headless browser** is a web browser without a graphical user interface.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] Headless browsers provide automated control of a web page in an environment similar to popular web browsers, but they are executed via a command-line interface or using network communication.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] They are particularly useful for testing web pages as they are able to render and understand HTML the same way a browser would, including styling elements such as page layout, color, font selection and execution of JavaScript and Ajax which are usually not available when using other testing methods.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] Since version 59 of Google Chrome and version 56 of Firefox, there is native support for remote control of the browser.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] This made earlier efforts obsolete, notably PhantomJS.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] Headless browsers are also useful for web scraping.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] Google stated in 2009 that using a headless browser could help their search engine index content from websites that use Ajax.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] However, a study of browser traffic in 2018 found no preference by malicious actors for headless browsers.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] There is no indication that headless browsers are used more frequently than non-headless browsers for malicious purposes, like DDoS attacks, SQL injections or cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] As several major browsers natively support headless mode through APIs, some software exists to perform browser automation through a unified interface.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] Some test automation software and frameworks include headless browsers as part of their testing apparati.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] Another approach is to use software that provides browser APIs.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] For example, Deno provides browser APIs as part of its design.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] For Node.js, jsdom is the most complete provider.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] While most are able to support common browser features (HTML parsing, cookies, XHR, some JavaScript, etc.), they do not render the DOM and have limited support for DOM events.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] They usually perform faster than full browsers, but are unable to correctly interpret many popular websites.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] Another is HtmlUnit, a headless browser written in Java.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] HtmlUnit uses the Rhino engine to provide JavaScript and Ajax support as well as partial rendering capability.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] These are various software that provide headless browser APIs.
[src:selenium-python/headless-browser] An earlier effort (2008) was envjs from John Resig, which was a simulated browser environment written in JavaScript for the Rhino engine.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] There are various strategies to locate elements in a page.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] You can use the most appropriate one for your case.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] The attributes available for the *By* class are used to locate elements on a page.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] The ‘By’ class is used to specify which attribute is used to locate elements on a page.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] If you want to locate several elements with the same attribute replace find_element with find_elements.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] Use this when you know the *id* attribute of an element.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] With this strategy, the first element with a matching *id* attribute will be returned.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] If no element has a matching *id* attribute, a `NoSuchElementException` will be raised.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] Use this when you know the *name* attribute of an element.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] With this strategy, the first element with a matching *name* attribute will be returned.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] If no element has a matching *name* attribute, a `NoSuchElementException` will be raised.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] XPath is the language used for locating nodes in an XML document.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] As HTML can be an implementation of XML (XHTML), Selenium users can leverage this powerful language to target elements in their web applications.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] XPath supports the simple methods of locating by id or name attributes and extends them by opening up all sorts of new possibilities such as locating the third checkbox on the page.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] One of the main reasons for using XPath is when you don’t have a suitable id or name attribute for the element you wish to locate.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] You can use XPath to either locate the element in absolute terms (not advised), or relative to an element that does have an id or name attribute.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] XPath locators can also be used to specify elements via attributes other than id and name.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] Absolute XPaths contain the location of all elements from the root (html) and as a result are likely to fail with only the slightest adjustment to the application.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] By finding a nearby element with an id or name attribute (ideally a parent element) you can locate your target element based on the relationship.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] This is much less likely to change and can make your tests more robust.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] Use this when you know the link text used within an anchor tag.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] With this strategy, the first element with the link text matching the provided value will be returned.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] If no element has a matching link text attribute, a `NoSuchElementException` will be raised.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] Use this when you want to locate an element by tag name.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] With this strategy, the first element with the given tag name will be returned.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] If no element has a matching tag name, a `NoSuchElementException` will be raised.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] Use this when you want to locate an element by class name.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] With this strategy, the first element with the matching class name attribute will be returned.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] If no element has a matching class name attribute, a `NoSuchElementException` will be raised.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] Use this when you want to locate an element using CSS selector syntax.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] With this strategy, the first element matching the given CSS selector will be returned.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] If no element matches the provided CSS selector, a `NoSuchElementException` will be raised.
[src:selenium-python/locating-elements] Sauce Labs has good documentation on CSS selectors.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium was originally developed by Jason Huggins in 2004 as an internal tool at ThoughtWorks.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Huggins was later joined by other programmers and testers at ThoughtWorks, before Paul Hammant joined the team and steered the development of the second mode of operation that would later become "Selenium Remote Control" (RC).
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] In 2005 Dan Fabulich and Nelson Sproul (with help from Pat Lightbody) made an offer to accept a series of patches that would transform Selenium-RC into what it became best known for.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] In the same meeting, the steering of Selenium as a project would continue as a committee, with Huggins and Hammant being the ThoughtWorks representatives.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Together with others like Jennifer Bevan, he continued with the development and stabilization of Selenium RC.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] At the same time, Simon Stewart at ThoughtWorks developed a superior browser automation tool called WebDriver.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] In 2009, after a meeting between the developers at the Google Test Automation Conference, it was decided to merge the two projects, and call the new project Selenium WebDriver, or Selenium 2.0.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] In 2008, Philippe Hanrigou (then at ThoughtWorks) made "Selenium Grid", which provides a hub allowing the running of multiple Selenium tests concurrently on any number of local or remote systems, thus minimizing test execution time.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Grid offered, as open source, a similar capability to the internal/private Google cloud for Selenium RC.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Pat Lightbody had already made a private cloud for "HostedQA" which he went on to sell to Gomez, Inc.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] The name Selenium comes from a joke made by Huggins in an email, mocking a competitor named Mercury, saying that mercury poisoning can be cured by taking supplements of the element selenium.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] The others that received the email took the name and ran with it.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium is composed of several components with each taking on a specific role in aiding the development of web application test automation.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium IDE is a complete integrated development environment (IDE) for Selenium tests.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] It is implemented as a Firefox Add-On and as a Chrome Extension.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] It allows for recording, editing and debugging of functional tests.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] It was previously known as Selenium Recorder.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium-IDE was originally created by Shinya Kasatani and donated to the Selenium project in 2006.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium IDE began being actively maintained in 2018.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Scripts may be automatically recorded and edited manually providing autocompletion support and the ability to move commands around quickly.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Scripts are recorded in *Selenese*, a special test scripting language for Selenium.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenese provides commands for performing actions in a browser (click a link, select an option) and for retrieving data from the resulting pages.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenese serves as the language for composing Selenium Commands, which are utilized in the testing of web applications.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] These commands, tailored to the HTML tags of UI elements, facilitate the verification of their existence.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] They guide Selenium in comprehending the specific actions or operations to execute.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] As an alternative to writing tests in Selenese, tests can also be written in various programming languages.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] These tests then communicate with Selenium by calling methods in the Selenium Client API.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium currently provides client APIs for Java, C#, Ruby, JavaScript, R and Python.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium Remote Control (RC) is a server, written in Java, that accepts commands for the browser via HTTP.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] RC makes it possible to write automated tests for a web application in any programming language, which allows for better integration of Selenium in existing unit test frameworks.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] To make writing tests easier, Selenium project currently provides client drivers for PHP, Python, Ruby, .NET, Perl and Java.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] The Java driver can also be used with JavaScript (via the Rhino engine).
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] An instance of selenium RC server is needed to launch html test case - which means that the port should be different for each parallel run.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] However, for Java/PHP test case only one Selenium RC instance needs to be running continuously.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium Remote Control was a refactoring of Driven Selenium or Selenium B designed by Paul Hammant, credited with Jason as co-creator of Selenium.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] The original version directly launched a process for the browser in question, from the test language of Java, .NET, Python or Ruby.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] The wire protocol (called 'Selenese' in its day) was reimplemented in each language port.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] After the refactor by Dan Fabulich and Nelson Sproul (with help from Pat Lightbody) there was an intermediate daemon process between the driving test script and the browser.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] The benefits included the ability to drive remote browsers and the reduced need to port every line of code to an increasingly growing set of languages.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] *Selenium Remote Control* completely took over from the Driven Selenium code-line in 2006.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] The browser pattern for 'Driven'/'B' and 'RC' was response/request, which subsequently became known as Comet.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium RC served as the flagship testing framework of the entire project of selenium for a long-standing time.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium RC is the first and foremost automated web testing tool that enabled users to adopt their preferred programming language.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] With the release of Selenium 2, Selenium RC has been officially deprecated in favor of Selenium WebDriver.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] At the core of Selenium is Selenium WebDriver, an interface to write instructions that work interchangeably across browsers.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium WebDriver accepts commands (sent in Selenese, or via a Client API) and sends them to a browser.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] This is implemented through a browser-specific browser driver, which sends commands to a browser and retrieves results.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Most browser drivers actually launch and access a browser application (such as Firefox, Google Chrome, Internet Explorer, Safari, or Microsoft Edge); there is also an HtmlUnit browser driver, which simulates a browser using the headless browser HtmlUnit.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Since Selenium 4 and Google Chrome version 109, headless mode has been supported through a native implementation of the browser, in which Chrome operates without a graphical user interface but with rendering and execution behavior identical to the regular mode.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Unlike in Selenium 1, where the Selenium server was necessary to run tests, Selenium WebDriver does not need a special server to execute tests.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Instead, the WebDriver directly starts a browser instance and controls it.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] However, Selenium Grid can be used with WebDriver to execute tests on remote systems (see below).
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Where possible, WebDriver uses native operating system level functionality rather than browser-based JavaScript commands to drive the browser.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] This bypasses problems with subtle differences between native and JavaScript commands, including security restrictions.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] As of early 2012, Simon Stewart (inventor of WebDriver), who was then with Google, and David Burns of Mozilla were negotiating with the W3C to make WebDriver an Internet standard.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] In July 2012, the working draft was released and the recommendation followed in June 2018.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium WebDriver (Selenium 2.0) is fully implemented and supported in JavaScript (Node.js), Python, Ruby, Java, Kotlin, and C#.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] As of 2021, Selenium 4 is a release candidate.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium Grid is a server that allows tests to use web browser instances running on remote machines.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] With Selenium Grid, one server acts as the central hub.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Tests contact the hub to obtain access to browser instances.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] The hub has a list of servers that provide access to browser instances (WebDriver nodes), and lets tests use these instances.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] Selenium Grid allows running tests in parallel on multiple machines and to manage different browser versions and browser configurations centrally (instead of in each individual test).
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] The ability to run tests on remote browser instances is useful to spread the load of testing across several machines and to run tests in browsers running on different platforms or operating systems.
[src:selenium-python/selenium-software] The latter is particularly useful in cases where not all browsers to be used for testing can run on the same platform.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] Automation provides many benefits over manual testing.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] For API testing, tests drive the SUT via its application programming interface (API).
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] Compared to manual testing, automated API testing often can execute a relatively large number of cases in a relatively short time.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] For GUI testing, tests drive the SUT via its graphical user interface (GUI) by generating events such as keystrokes and mouse clicks.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] Automated GUI testing can be challenging to develop, but can run much faster than a human could perform the same testing.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] When automated testing is in place, regression testing can be a relatively quick and easy operation.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] Instead of a significant outlay of human time and effort, a regression test run could require nothing more than a push of a button and even starting the run can be automated.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] The following are notable testing techniques categorized as test automation.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to assess the business risk of releasing the SUT.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] The scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] For model-based testing, the SUT is modeled and test cases can be generated from it to support no code test development.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] Some tools support the encoding of test cases as plain English that can be used on multiple operating systems, browsers, and smart devices.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] Test-driven development (TDD) inherently includes the generation of automation test code.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] Unit test code is written while the SUT code is written.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] When the code is complete, the tests are complete as well.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] A review of 52 practitioner and 26 academic sources found that five main factors to consider in test automation decision are: system under test (SUT), scope of testing, test toolset, human and organizational topics, cross-cutting factors.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] The factors most frequently identified were: need for regression testing, economic factors, and maturity of SUT.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] While the reusability of automated tests is valued by software development companies, this property can also be viewed as a disadvantage as it leads to a plateau effect, where repeatedly executing the same tests stops detecting errors.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] Testing tools can help automate tasks such as product installation, test data creation, GUI interaction, problem detection (consider parsing or polling agents equipped with test oracles), defect logging, etc., without necessarily automating tests in an end-to-end fashion.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] To support coded automated testing, the test engineer or software quality assurance person must have software coding ability.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] Some testing techniques such as table-driven and no-code can lessen or alleviate the need for programming skill.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] A test automation framework provides a programming environment that integrates test logic, test data, and other resources.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] The framework provides the basis of test automation and simplifies the automation effort.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] Using a framework can lower the cost of test development and maintenance.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] If there is change to any test case then only the test case file needs to be updated and the driver script and startup script will remain the same.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] A framework is responsible for defining the format in which to express expectations, providing a mechanism to hook into or drive the SUT, executing the tests, and reporting results.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] A test automation interface is a platform that provides a workspace for incorporating multiple testing tools and frameworks for system/integration testing.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] A test automation interface may simplify the process of mapping tests to business criteria without coding.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] A test automation interface may improve the efficiency and flexibility of maintaining tests.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] The parser is present to parse the object files coming from the object repository into the test specific scripting language.
[src:selenium-python/test-automation] Collection of UI/Application object data recorded by the testing tool while exploring the SUT.
